WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.620 --> 00:00:04.951
- Hello, everyone.

00:00:04.951 --> 00:00:07.450
It's very exciting to start out
this science lecture series.

00:00:07.450 --> 00:00:11.620
Sandro Galea was an emergency
physician and epidemiologist.

00:00:11.620 --> 00:00:14.536
He's the Robert
A. Knox professor

00:00:14.536 --> 00:00:15.910
and Dean of the
Boston University

00:00:15.910 --> 00:00:17.560
School of Public Health.

00:00:17.560 --> 00:00:19.330
He is the former
chair of epidemiology

00:00:19.330 --> 00:00:21.670
of the Columbia
University Mailman School

00:00:21.670 --> 00:00:23.260
of Public Health.

00:00:23.260 --> 00:00:25.840
Prior to his academic
career in public health,

00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:28.700
Dr. Galea practiced
emergency medicine in Canada

00:00:28.700 --> 00:00:31.750
and served in Somalia with
Doctors Without Borders.

00:00:31.750 --> 00:00:33.370
He was named one
of Time magazine's

00:00:33.370 --> 00:00:37.479
epidemiology innovators in
2006, and Thomas Reuters

00:00:37.479 --> 00:00:39.520
listed him as one of the
world's most influential

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:43.780
scientific minds for the
social sciences in 2015.

00:00:43.780 --> 00:00:47.320
Dr. Galea is a past president
of the Society for Epidemiologic

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:50.680
Research and elected member of
the American Epidemiological

00:00:50.680 --> 00:00:52.030
Society.

00:00:52.030 --> 00:00:54.850
He was elected to the National
Academy of Medicine in 2012

00:00:54.850 --> 00:00:58.180
and shared two of IOM's most
recent reports on mental health

00:00:58.180 --> 00:00:59.264
in the military.

00:00:59.264 --> 00:01:01.180
Dr. Galea serves frequently
on advisory groups

00:01:01.180 --> 00:01:03.072
of national and
international organizations.

00:01:03.072 --> 00:01:05.530
He formerly served as Chair of
the New York City Department

00:01:05.530 --> 00:01:08.980
of Health and Mental Hygiene's
community services board

00:01:08.980 --> 00:01:10.750
and as a member of
its health board.

00:01:10.750 --> 00:01:14.330
We are thrilled to have Dean
Galea here, and please join me

00:01:14.330 --> 00:01:15.432
in welcoming him.

00:01:15.432 --> 00:01:15.932
Thank you.

00:01:15.932 --> 00:01:19.369
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:25.555 --> 00:01:26.180
- Good evening.

00:01:26.180 --> 00:01:27.013
Thank you very much.

00:01:27.013 --> 00:01:29.720
Thank you, everybody, for
inviting me to come and present

00:01:29.720 --> 00:01:30.590
here.

00:01:30.590 --> 00:01:32.190
It's really a
pleasure to be here.

00:01:32.190 --> 00:01:35.750
So I'm delighted to open
this series, although I'm not

00:01:35.750 --> 00:01:39.470
entirely sure that I am going
to do justice to epidemics.

00:01:39.470 --> 00:01:41.740
Because my title is
about epidemiology

00:01:41.740 --> 00:01:47.482
counts, but I want to talk less
about the academic application

00:01:47.482 --> 00:01:49.940
of epidemiology, which those
of you who are not so inclined

00:01:49.940 --> 00:01:53.900
may be relieved, and more
about the core meaning

00:01:53.900 --> 00:01:54.840
of epidemiology.

00:01:54.840 --> 00:01:56.510
And by the core meaning
of epidemiology,

00:01:56.510 --> 00:02:00.350
I mean that, since epidemiology
became a discipline

00:02:00.350 --> 00:02:02.990
roughly 150 years ago,
the core definition

00:02:02.990 --> 00:02:06.500
has been that this epidemiology
is about understanding

00:02:06.500 --> 00:02:10.029
the causes of health so that
we may do something about them.

00:02:10.029 --> 00:02:11.570
So understanding
the causes of health

00:02:11.570 --> 00:02:13.194
so that we may do
something about them.

00:02:13.194 --> 00:02:15.749
And I actually think
that that meaning--

00:02:15.749 --> 00:02:17.540
so in my title, I said
epidemiology counts.

00:02:17.540 --> 00:02:18.770
I think that meaning counts.

00:02:18.770 --> 00:02:22.149
I think that it is important to
understand the causes of health

00:02:22.149 --> 00:02:23.690
so that we may do
something about it.

00:02:23.690 --> 00:02:25.340
And I'm going to
make an argument

00:02:25.340 --> 00:02:28.550
that how we think
about those causes

00:02:28.550 --> 00:02:32.360
has clear consequences for
whether we succeed in promoting

00:02:32.360 --> 00:02:33.750
healthy populations or not.

00:02:33.750 --> 00:02:35.240
So that's the arc of my talk.

00:02:35.240 --> 00:02:39.260
And I'm going to start off by
trying to lay out a challenge,

00:02:39.260 --> 00:02:41.750
and say, this is what
we'd like to get to.

00:02:41.750 --> 00:02:44.000
Point out some problems and
then offer some solutions.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:46.041
And then, of course, I
would be delighted to have

00:02:46.041 --> 00:02:46.850
some questions.

00:02:46.850 --> 00:02:49.040
So let me plunge right in.

00:02:49.040 --> 00:02:55.440
So let me start by arguing
that we want a healthier world.

00:02:55.440 --> 00:02:57.830
And when we say you
want a healthier world,

00:02:57.830 --> 00:03:02.000
it seems to me reasonable
that, if this is the world,

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:07.880
we are interested not simply
in a few people with disease,

00:03:07.880 --> 00:03:09.710
schematically.

00:03:09.710 --> 00:03:12.740
We're actually interested in
understanding the whole world

00:03:12.740 --> 00:03:15.701
and understanding a universe
of people who may have disease.

00:03:15.701 --> 00:03:16.200
Right?

00:03:16.200 --> 00:03:19.640
That our interests are
not particular to just

00:03:19.640 --> 00:03:20.360
a small group.

00:03:20.360 --> 00:03:22.990
We're interested in a
healthier world for all.

00:03:22.990 --> 00:03:26.570
It seems to me like
it's a tough argument

00:03:26.570 --> 00:03:29.340
to say that we want
something else.

00:03:29.340 --> 00:03:32.260
And ideally, we want to
understand the health for all,

00:03:32.260 --> 00:03:34.220
and assuming that the
people in the dark blue

00:03:34.220 --> 00:03:36.410
are disease people,
so that we actually

00:03:36.410 --> 00:03:37.420
make them better, right?

00:03:37.420 --> 00:03:38.510
So ultimately,
what we want to do

00:03:38.510 --> 00:03:39.968
is we want to
understand the world,

00:03:39.968 --> 00:03:42.560
understand about the disease,
and make some people better.

00:03:42.560 --> 00:03:44.600
That's ultimately
our aspiration.

00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:46.250
Now, I start with
this-- and this

00:03:46.250 --> 00:03:47.720
is a very, very simple concept.

00:03:47.720 --> 00:03:49.771
And you're going to say,
OK, OK, I know that.

00:03:49.771 --> 00:03:50.270
That's OK.

00:03:50.270 --> 00:03:53.450
But this has
implications for how

00:03:53.450 --> 00:03:56.480
we think about the cause of
health and the cause of disease

00:03:56.480 --> 00:03:59.190
and what we do about it,
as I'm going to get to.

00:03:59.190 --> 00:04:01.159
Now, let me start
with good news.

00:04:01.159 --> 00:04:02.200
I'm going to start with--

00:04:02.200 --> 00:04:03.881
there's abundant good news.

00:04:03.881 --> 00:04:05.880
One of the challenges of
being an epidemiologist

00:04:05.880 --> 00:04:08.270
or a public health person is
I always come to audiences

00:04:08.270 --> 00:04:10.790
and I talk about people dying
and being sick; it's all bad.

00:04:10.790 --> 00:04:12.206
So I want to start
with good news.

00:04:12.206 --> 00:04:13.490
All great stuff.

00:04:13.490 --> 00:04:17.750
This is the best slide I know
that says good news all around,

00:04:17.750 --> 00:04:19.040
which is this.

00:04:19.040 --> 00:04:23.570
So this is life expectancy
from the 1500s to the present,

00:04:23.570 --> 00:04:26.150
and what I want you to
see is the longest records

00:04:26.150 --> 00:04:28.330
of life expectancy
are in the UK,

00:04:28.330 --> 00:04:33.410
and life expectancy really
grumbled along around 40

00:04:33.410 --> 00:04:38.900
all the way till about 150 years
ago-- really in the mid 40s

00:04:38.900 --> 00:04:41.150
till about 100 years ago.

00:04:41.150 --> 00:04:45.470
So life expectancy grumbled
along, like, 40 to 45.

00:04:45.470 --> 00:04:48.630
And I would ask
everybody in this room,

00:04:48.630 --> 00:04:52.200
how would your life decisions
have been different had you

00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:54.652
expected to die at 45?

00:04:54.652 --> 00:04:57.430
And I mean, we all know
people do die at 45,

00:04:57.430 --> 00:04:58.630
but let's be honest.

00:04:58.630 --> 00:05:00.610
We expect to live
much longer than that.

00:05:00.610 --> 00:05:01.640
So, not so long ago--

00:05:01.640 --> 00:05:04.042
100 years ago-- we could
expect to live till 45.

00:05:04.042 --> 00:05:06.000
Now look what's happened
in the past 100 years.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:08.357
It's been this extraordinary
zooming upward.

00:05:08.357 --> 00:05:09.940
And these are just
selected countries.

00:05:09.940 --> 00:05:11.760
The United States is over--

00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:13.510
I can't remember which
one of these it is.

00:05:13.510 --> 00:05:14.426
And it's one of these.

00:05:14.426 --> 00:05:16.240
But we can see all
countries zooming up

00:05:16.240 --> 00:05:18.010
in the past 100 years.

00:05:18.010 --> 00:05:19.250
So that is extraordinary.

00:05:19.250 --> 00:05:21.010
Like, this is great good news.

00:05:21.010 --> 00:05:24.400
We haven't gained, in
the past hundred years,

00:05:24.400 --> 00:05:28.480
about a 40% increase in life
expectancy after having not

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:31.540
budged life expectancy
for hundreds of years.

00:05:31.540 --> 00:05:33.100
That is great good news.

00:05:33.100 --> 00:05:36.880
And you can see this good
news manifest in all sorts

00:05:36.880 --> 00:05:39.850
of other ways that
we measure health.

00:05:39.850 --> 00:05:41.600
So I'll give you
another example.

00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:45.100
This is global child mortality
between 1800 to the present,

00:05:45.100 --> 00:05:50.080
and the red is the
share of children

00:05:50.080 --> 00:05:52.510
who died before age
five, and the blue

00:05:52.510 --> 00:05:54.200
are the ones who
live past age five.

00:05:54.200 --> 00:05:55.100
So look at 1800.

00:05:55.100 --> 00:05:56.830
That's not that long ago.

00:05:56.830 --> 00:05:58.936
I understand in our
short lifespans,

00:05:58.936 --> 00:06:00.310
200 years seems
like a long time,

00:06:00.310 --> 00:06:02.597
but it's actually not that
long ago in human lifespan.

00:06:02.597 --> 00:06:04.930
Nearly half of all children
used to die before age five,

00:06:04.930 --> 00:06:06.100
and look at today.

00:06:06.100 --> 00:06:07.690
We're down to
under five percent.

00:06:07.690 --> 00:06:08.650
Right?

00:06:08.650 --> 00:06:10.400
So this is all good news.

00:06:10.400 --> 00:06:12.617
So we've done some things right.

00:06:12.617 --> 00:06:14.200
So I want to start
with the good news.

00:06:14.200 --> 00:06:15.790
Now, if it's all
a good news story,

00:06:15.790 --> 00:06:18.100
you probably don't need
to invite me to say, well,

00:06:18.100 --> 00:06:19.960
there are things that
we should do better.

00:06:19.960 --> 00:06:23.707
So let me talk a little bit
now about how we fall short.

00:06:23.707 --> 00:06:25.540
And I'm going to start
with a domestic lens,

00:06:25.540 --> 00:06:28.900
and then I'll-- for briefly,
I'll expand to a global lens.

00:06:28.900 --> 00:06:30.610
But let me start domestically.

00:06:30.610 --> 00:06:34.119
So this is a
sophisticated audience,

00:06:34.119 --> 00:06:36.160
so everybody is going to
know the first slide I'm

00:06:36.160 --> 00:06:37.460
going to show you.

00:06:37.460 --> 00:06:39.040
So the first slide I'm going
to show you, domestically,

00:06:39.040 --> 00:06:39.700
is this.

00:06:39.700 --> 00:06:42.270
But this is non-communicable
disease mortality.

00:06:42.270 --> 00:06:46.430
So is death from, essentially,
non-infectious diseases.

00:06:46.430 --> 00:06:48.460
The line between the two
blurs, but that's fine.

00:06:48.460 --> 00:06:49.835
And all I want
you to see here is

00:06:49.835 --> 00:06:52.540
that this is the US
comparing ourselves

00:06:52.540 --> 00:06:54.966
to any number of other
high income countries.

00:06:54.966 --> 00:06:56.590
You know, we're worse
even than Greece,

00:06:56.590 --> 00:06:58.631
and goodness knows they
can't get anything right,

00:06:58.631 --> 00:07:01.330
but we still kill more
people than they do.

00:07:01.330 --> 00:07:03.522
You know, Italy,
Japan, Spain etc.

00:07:03.522 --> 00:07:05.230
I always like putting
in Greece in there,

00:07:05.230 --> 00:07:06.580
because whenever I compare--

00:07:06.580 --> 00:07:08.290
like if I compare to
Sweden, everybody says, ach!

00:07:08.290 --> 00:07:10.581
But the Scandinavians, they're
just good at everything.

00:07:10.581 --> 00:07:12.850
But you know, hard to
argue the same for Greeks.

00:07:12.850 --> 00:07:16.900
So we have worse
life expectancy--

00:07:16.900 --> 00:07:19.810
I speak above people from
where I come from, so it's OK.

00:07:22.330 --> 00:07:23.410
But everybody knows this.

00:07:23.410 --> 00:07:29.200
You all know that life
expectancy, or the measure

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:32.416
on any number of health
outcomes in this country

00:07:32.416 --> 00:07:33.790
is worse than our
peer countries.

00:07:33.790 --> 00:07:36.160
Everybody walked into
this room knowing this.

00:07:36.160 --> 00:07:39.490
Now, what I suspect
you do not know

00:07:39.490 --> 00:07:43.250
is that it wasn't
always like this.

00:07:43.250 --> 00:07:46.460
And in fact, it wasn't
like this not so long ago.

00:07:46.460 --> 00:07:48.190
So let me show
you another graph.

00:07:48.190 --> 00:07:51.620
So the way to read this is,
this is 1980 to the present.

00:07:51.620 --> 00:07:53.870
These are the OECD countries--
high income countries.

00:07:53.870 --> 00:07:55.397
There are 17 of them.

00:07:55.397 --> 00:07:56.980
The gray dots are
all these countries,

00:07:56.980 --> 00:07:58.930
the red dot is the US.

00:07:58.930 --> 00:08:01.690
So in 1980, we were
in the top half.

00:08:01.690 --> 00:08:03.700
Everybody see the
life expectancy?

00:08:03.700 --> 00:08:06.850
And over the course
of the past 35 years,

00:08:06.850 --> 00:08:08.650
we have steadily
drifted to the bottom.

00:08:08.650 --> 00:08:10.910
Now, there's an
upward slope here,

00:08:10.910 --> 00:08:12.834
so our life expectancy
has been going up,

00:08:12.834 --> 00:08:14.750
but at a much slower
rate than everybody else.

00:08:14.750 --> 00:08:17.500
So we now have the
worst life expectancy

00:08:17.500 --> 00:08:21.130
of any of our high income peers.

00:08:21.130 --> 00:08:24.070
The bad news is that
we have wrought this

00:08:24.070 --> 00:08:26.570
upon ourselves in 35 years.

00:08:26.570 --> 00:08:28.850
The good news is, well, if
we've done it in 35 years,

00:08:28.850 --> 00:08:31.300
we should be able to reverse it
over the next 35 years, right?

00:08:31.300 --> 00:08:32.140
That's the good news.

00:08:32.140 --> 00:08:33.473
This is clearly not intractable.

00:08:33.473 --> 00:08:35.799
Because I feel like
the public discussion--

00:08:35.799 --> 00:08:39.730
the informed public
discussion about US health--

00:08:39.730 --> 00:08:42.657
often stops at the slide
and says, oh, it's terrible.

00:08:42.657 --> 00:08:43.240
It's terrible.

00:08:43.240 --> 00:08:44.090
We're worse than everybody else.

00:08:44.090 --> 00:08:44.719
Yes, we are.

00:08:44.719 --> 00:08:46.010
But we weren't always that bad.

00:08:46.010 --> 00:08:49.510
We actually-- not so long
ago, we were not that bad.

00:08:49.510 --> 00:08:50.650
Now how bad are we now?

00:08:50.650 --> 00:08:53.480
I just want to deepen
the misery for a second.

00:08:53.480 --> 00:08:58.510
So I'm going to show you
two slides about mortality

00:08:58.510 --> 00:09:01.780
in the US compared to median
mortality in high income

00:09:01.780 --> 00:09:02.745
countries.

00:09:02.745 --> 00:09:04.120
And I'm just going
to divide them

00:09:04.120 --> 00:09:05.720
by age, just to make the point.

00:09:05.720 --> 00:09:07.870
So let me start
with young people.

00:09:07.870 --> 00:09:12.070
And by young, here, I take the
liberal definition of under 75.

00:09:12.070 --> 00:09:16.090
So young people under
75 75 is the new 55.

00:09:16.090 --> 00:09:18.370
We all know that.

00:09:18.370 --> 00:09:20.200
So here are people under 75.

00:09:20.200 --> 00:09:22.000
So here's the way to read this--

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:26.170
the blue is mortality
in the US, the red

00:09:26.170 --> 00:09:30.050
is median mortality in all the
other high income countries.

00:09:30.050 --> 00:09:32.939
So what you see;
under one, one to 14.

00:09:32.939 --> 00:09:35.230
So first of all, you see this
U-shaped mortality curve.

00:09:35.230 --> 00:09:36.139
That's very standard.

00:09:36.139 --> 00:09:38.680
We have more mortality at the
youngest stages, more mortality

00:09:38.680 --> 00:09:39.580
as you older, right?

00:09:39.580 --> 00:09:41.260
Nothing surprising there.

00:09:41.260 --> 00:09:42.490
But then look at this.

00:09:42.490 --> 00:09:46.380
We kill more newborns than
anybody else, you know,

00:09:46.380 --> 00:09:47.080
and that's not--

00:09:47.080 --> 00:09:48.950
the safest age to be
is always one to 14.

00:09:48.950 --> 00:09:50.590
That's like when you
live, and then you

00:09:50.590 --> 00:09:52.070
start killing people again.

00:09:52.070 --> 00:09:52.870
But look at this--

00:09:52.870 --> 00:09:55.060
the blue bar is always
higher than the red bar.

00:09:55.060 --> 00:09:58.690
So we are consistent that we
kill more people at all age

00:09:58.690 --> 00:10:00.340
groups than all the
other high income

00:10:00.340 --> 00:10:03.190
countries, which at least
would give us for consistency.

00:10:03.190 --> 00:10:06.970
So that's slide A, but now let
me show you the second slide.

00:10:06.970 --> 00:10:09.220
If I may take the
liberty to say over 75

00:10:09.220 --> 00:10:12.130
is the older age group--
not old, just older.

00:10:12.130 --> 00:10:14.710
So now let's flip to over 75.

00:10:14.710 --> 00:10:16.270
So these are over 75.

00:10:16.270 --> 00:10:18.230
And now you see, again,
US and other countries.

00:10:18.230 --> 00:10:20.110
So this is 75 to 79.

00:10:20.110 --> 00:10:21.430
Roughly even.

00:10:21.430 --> 00:10:25.380
Over 80 we're less,
85 we're less, 95-99,

00:10:25.380 --> 00:10:27.670
100 plus were less.

00:10:27.670 --> 00:10:33.690
So we actually are doing great
in mortality over age 75.

00:10:33.690 --> 00:10:35.566
So this is an amazing
country to live in

00:10:35.566 --> 00:10:36.940
as long as you
live until age 75,

00:10:36.940 --> 00:10:38.190
because then you live forever.

00:10:38.190 --> 00:10:39.600
Because then, nobody dies.

00:10:39.600 --> 00:10:44.570
If you go to, like, 150, our
mortality goes really way down.

00:10:44.570 --> 00:10:47.590
So when you compare
how we're doing

00:10:47.590 --> 00:10:50.950
to these other high income
countries and just rank us.

00:10:50.950 --> 00:10:52.690
So you rank us, one through 17.

00:10:52.690 --> 00:10:53.960
There are 17 OECD countries.

00:10:53.960 --> 00:10:54.694
One through 17.

00:10:54.694 --> 00:10:55.360
What's our rank?

00:10:55.360 --> 00:10:56.444
So here's a graph of that.

00:10:56.444 --> 00:10:58.818
The way to [INAUDIBLE] these
ranks, [INAUDIBLE] 17, so 17

00:10:58.818 --> 00:10:59.440
is bad.

00:10:59.440 --> 00:11:00.580
There are two lines
