00:12:55.290 --> 00:12:57.090
is higher than all these other
countries I showed you before,

00:12:57.090 --> 00:12:57.590
right?

00:12:57.590 --> 00:12:58.960
So nothing surprising there.

00:12:58.960 --> 00:13:00.335
But all I want to
do here is, I'm

00:13:00.335 --> 00:13:02.770
going to add one more country.

00:13:02.770 --> 00:13:06.300
I'm going to add to
this graph Ethiopia.

00:13:06.300 --> 00:13:09.064
So maternal mortality,
I add Ethiopia.

00:13:09.064 --> 00:13:09.730
That's Ethiopia.

00:13:09.730 --> 00:13:10.646
That's the same graph.

00:13:10.646 --> 00:13:12.710
Let me go back.

00:13:12.710 --> 00:13:14.120
You see these countries here?

00:13:14.120 --> 00:13:15.160
Just look at the axis.

00:13:15.160 --> 00:13:16.610
0 to 16.

00:13:16.610 --> 00:13:19.280
Now the axis is in the 0 to 400
scale, because that's the US

00:13:19.280 --> 00:13:20.390
and that's Ethiopia.

00:13:20.390 --> 00:13:23.630
So I just did want to, for
a second, take us out a lens

00:13:23.630 --> 00:13:26.210
to say that, while I was
talking about the domestic lens,

00:13:26.210 --> 00:13:28.520
there is absolutely no
reason why we don't take

00:13:28.520 --> 00:13:31.122
a global lens, and from point
of view of health equity,

00:13:31.122 --> 00:13:33.080
there is absolutely no
reason why this happens.

00:13:33.080 --> 00:13:35.400
This is just as
unacceptable as is that.

00:13:35.400 --> 00:13:35.900
OK?

00:13:35.900 --> 00:13:38.870
So I just want to label
that, that these issues are--

00:13:38.870 --> 00:13:41.740
one can take a national lens
as well as a global lens.

00:13:41.740 --> 00:13:45.860
Now, let me get to the
crux of my argument.

00:13:45.860 --> 00:13:46.912
So where do we go wrong?

00:13:46.912 --> 00:13:48.620
And I want to make a
three part argument,

00:13:48.620 --> 00:13:51.590
and then I will counter it with
a sort of three part solution

00:13:51.590 --> 00:13:53.960
just for the sake of symmetry.

00:13:53.960 --> 00:13:56.420
And why is this the case?

00:13:56.420 --> 00:13:59.960
Now, there's plenty
of blame to go around,

00:13:59.960 --> 00:14:04.430
and I approach this very much
from the perspective of someone

00:14:04.430 --> 00:14:09.050
who has spent my professional
adult life, really,

00:14:09.050 --> 00:14:09.980
within the Academy.

00:14:09.980 --> 00:14:12.869
So I tend to tend
to try to figure out

00:14:12.869 --> 00:14:15.410
where I've gone wrong, where we
collectively have gone wrong,

00:14:15.410 --> 00:14:16.910
rather than trying
to point fingers

00:14:16.910 --> 00:14:18.666
at broader, other forces.

00:14:18.666 --> 00:14:20.165
But with that in
mind, I think there

00:14:20.165 --> 00:14:21.950
are three places we
have gone wrong, which

00:14:21.950 --> 00:14:25.970
I think gets at this notion I
was trying to make that, if we

00:14:25.970 --> 00:14:29.700
understand the causes of health,
that has real consequences

00:14:29.700 --> 00:14:30.950
and allows us to act properly.

00:14:30.950 --> 00:14:32.241
So three ways we've gone wrong.

00:14:32.241 --> 00:14:34.150
Number one.

00:14:34.150 --> 00:14:38.770
Number one, we lose sight
of what causes health.

00:14:38.770 --> 00:14:42.130
Now, you all say, well, I
know what causes health.

00:14:42.130 --> 00:14:44.910
Well, you know, heart disease
and stroke and cancer,

00:14:44.910 --> 00:14:47.170
et cetera.

00:14:47.170 --> 00:14:50.280
So, that's not quite right.

00:14:50.280 --> 00:14:54.420
And I want to illustrate what
causes health with a story.

00:14:54.420 --> 00:14:56.380
So This is a blues man.

00:14:56.380 --> 00:14:58.420
His name was Blind
Willie Johnson.

00:14:58.420 --> 00:15:00.711
So this is the only known
photograph of Willie Johnson.

00:15:00.711 --> 00:15:03.340
Any of you who like the blues
will know Blind Willie Johnson.

00:15:03.340 --> 00:15:06.940
He was born at the turn of
the 19th century in Texas.

00:15:06.940 --> 00:15:10.830
And he was born in
Texas, he was poor.

00:15:10.830 --> 00:15:13.320
The story is that
when he was three,

00:15:13.320 --> 00:15:17.700
his mother threw lye in his eyes
in an act of domestic violence,

00:15:17.700 --> 00:15:19.980
and he became blind.

00:15:19.980 --> 00:15:22.380
He lived fairly poor.

00:15:22.380 --> 00:15:24.030
He learned how to
play the guitar,

00:15:24.030 --> 00:15:27.201
he made money playing
the blues, and he busked.

00:15:27.201 --> 00:15:28.950
Essentially, that's
the way he made money.

00:15:28.950 --> 00:15:31.920
He was married, he lived in a
house, the house burned down,

00:15:31.920 --> 00:15:33.600
he had no money so
he continued living

00:15:33.600 --> 00:15:35.110
in the burned down house.

00:15:35.110 --> 00:15:39.460
And when he was 44,
he developed malaria.

00:15:39.460 --> 00:15:41.430
So blind Willie Johnson,
who was blind, poor,

00:15:41.430 --> 00:15:44.630
and black in Texas, and
this is now in the 40s--

00:15:44.630 --> 00:15:47.100
1940s-- his wife took
him to the hospital,

00:15:47.100 --> 00:15:48.157
where he was turned away.

00:15:48.157 --> 00:15:50.490
Unclear whether he was turned
away because he was blind,

00:15:50.490 --> 00:15:53.190
because he was black, because
he was poor; and went home

00:15:53.190 --> 00:15:54.860
and died.

00:15:54.860 --> 00:15:57.350
So the question is, what
killed Blind Willie Johnson?

00:15:57.350 --> 00:15:59.339
Well, obviously the
malaria killed him, right?

00:15:59.339 --> 00:16:01.130
But it wasn't just
malaria that killed him.

00:16:01.130 --> 00:16:01.629
Right?

00:16:01.629 --> 00:16:03.630
It was his malaria,
it was racism,

00:16:03.630 --> 00:16:06.684
it was domestic
violence, it was poverty.

00:16:06.684 --> 00:16:09.100
All of that killed Blind Willie
if malaria didn't get him,

00:16:09.100 --> 00:16:11.410
something else was going
to get him any day, right?

00:16:11.410 --> 00:16:13.900
Now, why am I telling you
this obvious, obvious story?

00:16:13.900 --> 00:16:16.780
I'm telling this obvious
story because unless we

00:16:16.780 --> 00:16:21.340
ground a conversation in the
foundational causes of health--

00:16:21.340 --> 00:16:25.600
unless we understand
that, if we fix malaria,

00:16:25.600 --> 00:16:29.350
and we don't deal with the
racism, with the poverty,

00:16:29.350 --> 00:16:31.540
with the domestic
violence, we are not

00:16:31.540 --> 00:16:33.490
going to fix health for all.

00:16:33.490 --> 00:16:35.540
We actually go down a
totally different path.

00:16:35.540 --> 00:16:37.360
So I'm starting with
an obvious story.

00:16:37.360 --> 00:16:41.380
Now, I would argue that
while this may be obvious,

00:16:41.380 --> 00:16:43.860
this is in no way where our
national conversation is at.

00:16:43.860 --> 00:16:44.920
And that's bad news.

00:16:44.920 --> 00:16:47.070
But here's good news, perhaps--

00:16:47.070 --> 00:16:49.750
that this kind of battle
about what causes health,

00:16:49.750 --> 00:16:56.410
we have been having in the
world for hundreds of years.

00:16:56.410 --> 00:16:57.930
Here's a classic example.

00:16:57.930 --> 00:17:01.220
These two generously
mustachioed gentlemen

00:17:01.220 --> 00:17:05.929
are two of the founding
fathers of public health.

00:17:05.929 --> 00:17:08.700
The gentleman on the left is
Edwin Chadwick, the gentleman

00:17:08.700 --> 00:17:10.579
on the right, William Farr.

00:17:10.579 --> 00:17:14.630
And William Farr is
credited with being

00:17:14.630 --> 00:17:16.490
the father of statistics.

00:17:16.490 --> 00:17:19.430
He started life table
counting in the UK.

00:17:19.430 --> 00:17:22.520
Edwin Chadwick is the
architect of the British Health

00:17:22.520 --> 00:17:26.390
Act of 1848, which was one of
the sentinel health acts that

00:17:26.390 --> 00:17:28.410
created health in cities.

00:17:28.410 --> 00:17:30.710
But they had a big
argument, and the argument

00:17:30.710 --> 00:17:34.220
was as follows-- that William
Farr, who was counting deaths,

00:17:34.220 --> 00:17:38.780
said that the babies
of poor mothers

00:17:38.780 --> 00:17:41.420
were dying more than
babies of rich mothers.

00:17:41.420 --> 00:17:44.760
So he said, poverty is
killing these babies.

00:17:44.760 --> 00:17:49.206
Edwin Chadwick was a
politician, and he said--

00:17:49.206 --> 00:17:50.830
and there's a quote
which I'm not going

00:17:50.830 --> 00:17:52.780
to get exactly right, but--

00:17:52.780 --> 00:17:57.607
babies do not die of
poverty in civilized London.

00:17:57.607 --> 00:17:58.690
He says, it's not poverty.

00:17:58.690 --> 00:17:59.640
So what was it?

00:17:59.640 --> 00:18:01.570
Well, it was
nutritional deficiency,

00:18:01.570 --> 00:18:03.929
said Chadwick, that was killing
the babies, not poverty.

00:18:03.929 --> 00:18:05.470
And the argument
went back and forth,

00:18:05.470 --> 00:18:06.886
because Chadwick
was a politician;

00:18:06.886 --> 00:18:09.940
Chadwick won, and nutritional
deficiency was recorded.

00:18:09.940 --> 00:18:11.440
But the reason I'm
showing this is

00:18:11.440 --> 00:18:14.440
because this gets at
the heart of how we

00:18:14.440 --> 00:18:15.876
think about what causes health.

00:18:15.876 --> 00:18:16.750
Now, how about today?

00:18:16.750 --> 00:18:18.430
What is the
implication for today?

00:18:18.430 --> 00:18:21.010
In Epidemiology 101,
Public Health 101,

00:18:21.010 --> 00:18:23.051
any health 101 class
anywhere in the country,

00:18:23.051 --> 00:18:25.300
you will have a discussion
of a table like this, which

00:18:25.300 --> 00:18:27.850
says the causes of death
in the United States

00:18:27.850 --> 00:18:29.770
are heart disease,
stroke, et cetera;

00:18:29.770 --> 00:18:32.950
or tobacco, poor diet,
alcohol consumption, bugs,

00:18:32.950 --> 00:18:34.969
toxic agents, etc.

00:18:34.969 --> 00:18:36.760
And these are the
[INAUDIBLE] those people.

00:18:36.760 --> 00:18:38.410
But is that what causes health?

00:18:38.410 --> 00:18:40.300
Or is this what causes health?

00:18:40.300 --> 00:18:42.550
Low education, low social
support, racial segregation,

00:18:42.550 --> 00:18:44.050
income inequality, poverty.

00:18:44.050 --> 00:18:46.270
Look at the number
of deaths from this.

00:18:46.270 --> 00:18:48.127
Low education, 190,000.

00:18:48.127 --> 00:18:49.710
Acute heart attacks,
roughly the same.

00:18:49.710 --> 00:18:51.670
Low social support,
stroke, roughly the same.

00:18:51.670 --> 00:18:53.500
Racial segregation,
lung cancer, the same.

00:18:53.500 --> 00:18:57.670
Obviously, all of these
are causes of health.

00:18:57.670 --> 00:19:00.400
I'm in no way saying
it's this, not that.

00:19:00.400 --> 00:19:02.530
But what I'm saying
is that, unless we

00:19:02.530 --> 00:19:08.120
keep our eye on the multiplicity
of causes of health,

00:19:08.120 --> 00:19:11.920
we will not invest in
these other causes.

00:19:11.920 --> 00:19:13.630
To go back to the
Willy Johnson example,

00:19:13.630 --> 00:19:16.630
we'll invest only in malaria and
forget about everything else.

00:19:16.630 --> 00:19:18.852
Now you say to me, oh,
we're better than that.

00:19:18.852 --> 00:19:19.810
We're better than that.

00:19:19.810 --> 00:19:20.620
We understand this.

00:19:20.620 --> 00:19:21.370
We understand this.

00:19:21.370 --> 00:19:21.880
There, there.

00:19:21.880 --> 00:19:22.838
Why don't you sit down.

00:19:22.838 --> 00:19:23.380
We get this.

00:19:23.380 --> 00:19:25.213
We know that these
things matter for health.

00:19:25.213 --> 00:19:27.660
Of course we invest in them
when it comes to health.

00:19:27.660 --> 00:19:29.420
But do we?

00:19:29.420 --> 00:19:30.601
Now, we're in Massachusetts.

00:19:30.601 --> 00:19:32.600
We have the privilege of
being probably the most

00:19:32.600 --> 00:19:35.030
progressive state
in the country.

00:19:35.030 --> 00:19:38.580
Do we understand this
in Massachusetts?

00:19:38.580 --> 00:19:41.230
Does our money follow
where our ideas are?

00:19:41.230 --> 00:19:44.080
Let's look at where health
spending is in Massachusetts.

00:19:44.080 --> 00:19:47.650
Massachusetts health spending.

00:19:47.650 --> 00:19:49.080
These are causes of health.

00:19:49.080 --> 00:19:50.955
It's a real schematic.

00:19:50.955 --> 00:19:53.192
You know, access to
care, most people

00:19:53.192 --> 00:19:54.400
think it's about five to 10%.

00:19:54.400 --> 00:19:56.680
Genetics, socioeconomic
physical environments,

00:19:56.680 --> 00:19:59.080
healthy behaviors,
interaction about everything.

00:19:59.080 --> 00:20:00.250
Here's our spending.

00:20:00.250 --> 00:20:02.460
90% of our spending is
on medical services,

00:20:02.460 --> 00:20:04.270
but less than 10% is
on healthy behaviors.

00:20:04.270 --> 00:20:09.640
Most estimates are that we
spend 3% to 5% on things

00:20:09.640 --> 00:20:12.886
that aim at prevention.

00:20:12.886 --> 00:20:13.760
How has this changed?

00:20:13.760 --> 00:20:15.480
You're like, OK, well, maybe
this was bad over time,

00:20:15.480 --> 00:20:16.110
but it's changing.

00:20:16.110 --> 00:20:17.010
We're getting better.

00:20:17.010 --> 00:20:18.500
Let's look at change over time.

00:20:18.500 --> 00:20:22.130
Past 15 years, Massachusetts
spending 2001-2014.

00:20:22.130 --> 00:20:26.169
We have increased our
spending in medical care 81%.

00:20:26.169 --> 00:20:28.210
Kept the same or decreased,
primary and secondary

00:20:28.210 --> 00:20:29.520
education, law and public
safety, mental health,

00:20:29.520 --> 00:20:31.120
public health, higher education,
early child education,

00:20:31.120 --> 00:20:32.490
and environmental education.

00:20:32.490 --> 00:20:36.730
So you tell me that we actually
understand the Blind Willie

00:20:36.730 --> 00:20:38.280
story.

00:20:38.280 --> 00:20:42.570
Because surely if we understood
it, we would not be doing this,

00:20:42.570 --> 00:20:44.620
right?

00:20:44.620 --> 00:20:47.610
And this, of course,
directly maps on

00:20:47.610 --> 00:20:49.980
to the slides I
showed you earlier

00:20:49.980 --> 00:20:53.110
that talk about the
fact that the US spends

00:20:53.110 --> 00:20:56.530
far more than anybody else
and has far worse health

00:20:56.530 --> 00:20:57.872
indicators.

00:20:57.872 --> 00:21:00.080
Because of course we are
spending more than everybody

00:21:00.080 --> 00:21:02.150
else, but we're
spending it on just one

00:21:02.150 --> 00:21:04.040
aspect of what causes health.

00:21:04.040 --> 00:21:06.500
In some respects, if
the audience actually

00:21:06.500 --> 00:21:08.480
understands that point,
my work here is done.

00:21:08.480 --> 00:21:12.680
Because the core point is that
if one thinks about the causes

00:21:12.680 --> 00:21:14.550
of health-- remember,
that's how I started--

00:21:14.550 --> 00:21:17.630
and one understands that
there's a full range of causes.

00:21:17.630 --> 00:21:20.240
If we're spending on
only one of those causes,

00:21:20.240 --> 00:21:24.070
we are inevitably going
to be underperforming.

00:21:24.070 --> 00:21:27.340
I want to show you
a metaphor, and then

00:21:27.340 --> 00:21:30.985
move onto the second thing
I think we're doing wrong.

00:21:30.985 --> 00:21:32.860
So this is the best
soccer team in the world.

00:21:32.860 --> 00:21:35.470
This is the US Women's
National Soccer Team.

00:21:35.470 --> 00:21:39.061
And I know that soccer is not
the most popular sport here,

00:21:39.061 --> 00:21:41.060
although in Massachusetts,
it's probably better.

00:21:41.060 --> 00:21:42.730
But for those who don't
know how the game is played,

00:21:42.730 --> 00:21:45.530
there are 11 people on one
side, 11 people in the other,

00:21:45.530 --> 00:21:49.352
and they get the ball to the
